hopobject.body: i'm fine good work alesse generic equivalent Those who consider the 23-percent gap to be a myth often claim it's a function of education and career choices. Women more often choose low-wage occupations like social work, for example, while men more often become engineers. Likewise, women also often work fewer hours or even leave work altogether for a time to raise children, which derails their earnings trajectory. Several studies have shown that these sorts of choices account for a large chunk of the wage gap.
